The Telegraph - Calcutta
 Thursday, October 10, 2002  The City Diary
				 																																										A number of fires broke out in and around the city on Wednesday. At Dhakuria, there was a blaze in a puja pandal which was doused by two fire engines. Another fire broke out in the office of the superintendent of police of South 24-Parganas as result of a technical fault in electrical installations. Two fire engines were deployed to control the blaze. The office went without power for more than seven hours from 12 noon. Another fire broke out in a factory at Sonarpur in the morning. Machines and papers were damaged. Four fire engines fought the blaze for two hours. No one was injured, fire brigade sources said.				 																																										In a pre-puja drive about 10,000 criminals wanted in various cases were arrested in Behala, Jadavpur, Regent Park, Kasba, Tiljala and different places of South 24-Parganas. District superintendent of police Deb Kumar Ganguly said a huge cache of arms was recovered from them. To ensure that peace prevails during Durga Puja, a number of steps have been taken which include deployment of about 4,000 policemen, two platoons of RAF and EFR personnel and setting up of two watch towers on Eastern Metropolitan Bypass to keep a watch on the crowd. 				 																																										Two newly-married women were murdered allegedly by their in-laws in Barasat on Tuesday. Police said Sipra Sen, 18, was married to Susanta of Halisahar only two months ago. Her parents compla-ined that she was tortured for more dowry. Her in-laws are absconding. In the second incident, 26-year-old Sipra Roy, married to Amal Roy of Jagatdal, died of burns. Her parents alleged that she was killed by her in-laws, who poured kerosene on her and set her on fire. Her husband was arrested.				 																																										Sujit Sarkar, 68, a retired driver of Medical College and Hospital, committed suicide by hanging himself, from the ceiling of his room on Sahitya Parishad Street, in the Battala area, on Tuesday. Police said Sarkar was suffering from depression.				 																																										At least a dozen supporters of SFI and Chhatra Parishad were injured after the police resorted to a lathicharge at Fakir Chand College, in Diamond Harbour, on Wednesday. The clash broke out after some students tore off the BA and B.Sc results pasted on the notice board. The college authorities said the police had to be called in as the situation spun out of control. The police denied the allegation of the lathicharge. All the injured students were admitted to a local hospital. Of them, the condition of Uttam Haldar, an SFI member, was said to be in a critical condition.				 																																										The state government will take steps against those involved in Tuesdays assault on an officer of the Rishra Hastings Jute Mill, Subrata Chakraborty. On Wednesday, labour minister Mohammed Amin denounced the attack at Writers Buildings and appealed to the workers to maintain peace. On Tuesday, Chakraborty was attacked when he came out of his office after attending a meeting.				 																																										The vacation bench of Calcutta High Court will sit almost every day now except for the four days of Durga Puja and the three days of Lakshmi puja, Kali puja and Bhratridwitiya.				 																																										The chief metropolitan magistrate of Calcutta on Wednesday rejected the bail petition of Jitendra Majithia and Dinesh Shah, board members of Calcutta Gujarati Education Society, who were arrested on Tuesday night for their alleged involvement in defalcation of society funds. The magistrate sent them to jail custody till Saturday.				 																																										According to the prosecution, the two board members connived with managers of the three banks to siphon off more than Rs 4 crores. The society had lodged a complaint with the police after the banks refused to respond when the society wanted to draw money from fixed deposits. 				 																																										O rotary club of belvedere gardens for organising a free heart check-up and cancer detection camp at Park Circus
